eams/img title=image src=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/b2-img/2009/05/image.png alt=image width=200 height=120 //a/p\npTwo column, widget ready, gravatar ready, totally blue theme./p\npa href=http://www.varometro.net/blog/r755_theme/R755/a/p\npimg title=r755 src=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/b2-img/2009/05/r755.png alt=r755 width=200 height=150 //p\npR755 is a wordpress theme built from scratch with two basic principles: content comes first and the smallest possible size. Valid CSS and XHTML (Strict), threaded-comments, microformats, sticky-post, SEO./p\npa href=http://www.cssjockey.com/imagination/Imagination/a/p\npimg title=image src=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/b2-img/2009/05/image1.png alt=image width=200 height=125 //p\npCompletely customizable two column theme, preloaded with several styles with built-in support for twitter, Flickr, Feedburner etc./p\npa href=http://izandi.net/2009/04/free-2-column-wordpress-themes/Wave/a/p\npa href=http://izandi.net/Free_WordPress_Themes/Wave/img title=image src=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/b2-img/2009/05/image2.png alt=image width=200 height=125 //a/p\npTwo column blue theme with a widgetized left sidebar./p";}i:17;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:50:"Weblog Tools Collection: Smarter Theme Development";s:4:"guid";s:40:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/?p=5720";s:4:"link";s:79:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2009/05/01/smarter-theme-development/";s:11:"description";s:975:"pIan Stewart who is the creator of the a href=http://themeshaper.com/thematic/ target=_blankThematic theme framework/a is currently in the process of putting together a series which explains how to cut theme development time, easier theme modifications, and the power of child themes. The first two parts of this guide are already online and covers a href=http://themeshaper.com/wordpress-child-theme-basics/ target=_blankchild theme basics/a and a href=http://themeshaper.com/modular-css-wordpress-child-themes/ target=_blankmodular CSS in child themes/a. Ian plans on covering the following topics in the future:/p\nul\nliUsing Filter Hooks in WordPress Child Themes/li\nliUsing Action Hooks in WordPress Child Themes/li\nliCreating WordPress Child Themes/li\nliPublicly Releasing WordPress Child Themes/li\n/ul\npAlthough this guide ends up using Thematic as the prime example, you should be able to pick up a few tips and tricks to implement if you#8217;re not using Thematic./p";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Fri, 01 May 2009 22:14:12 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:13:"Jeff Chandler";}s:7:"summary";s:975:"pIan Stewart who is the creator of the a href=http://themeshaper.com/thematic/ target=_blankThematic theme framework/a is currently in the process of putting together a series which explains how to cut theme development time, easier theme modifications, and the power of child themes. The first two parts of this guide are already online and covers a href=http://themeshaper.com/wordpress-child-theme-basics/ target=_blankchild theme basics/a and a href=http://themeshaper.com/modular-css-wordpress-child-themes/ target=_blankmodular CSS in child themes/a. Ian plans on covering the following topics in the future:/p\nul\nliUsing Filter Hooks in WordPress Child Themes/li\nliUsing Action Hooks in WordPress Child Themes/li\nliCreating WordPress Child Themes/li\nliPublicly Releasing WordPress Child Themes/li\n/ul\npAlthough this guide ends up using Thematic as the prime example, you should be able to pick up a few tips and tricks to implement if you#8217;re not using Thematic./p";}i:18;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:53:"Weblog Tools Collection: BuddyPress 1.0 Has Arrived!!";s:4:"guid";s:40:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/?p=5713";s:4:"link";s:79:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2009/04/30/buddypress-10-has-arrived/";s:11:"description";s:609:"pa href=http://buddypress.org/blog/news/buddypress-10-has-arrived/BuddyPress 1.0 Has Arrived/a.: Andy announced the release of BuddyPress 1.0 on the BuddyPress community Blog and there was much rejoicing. This was an excellent opportunity to get my WLTC Community project off the ground and I was an like installation fiend as soon as I finished work on my day job./p\npSo without further ado, especially if you want to play around with BuddyPress, please head over to the strongshiny new a href=http://midout.comWLTC Community/a/strong and register for either a username or a blog. I hope to meet you there!/p";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Fri, 01 May 2009 02:18:14 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:10:"Mark Ghosh";}s:7:"summary";s:609:"pa href=http://buddypress.org/blog/news/buddypress-10-has-arrived/BuddyPress 1.0 Has Arrived/a.: Andy announced the release of BuddyPress 1.0 on the BuddyPress community Blog and there was much rejoicing. This was an excellent opportunity to get my WLTC Community project off the ground and I was an like installation fiend as soon as I finished work on my day job./p\npSo without further ado, especially if you want to play around with BuddyPress, please head over to the strongshiny new a href=http://midout.comWLTC Community/a/strong and register for either a username or a blog. I hope to meet you there!/p";}i:19;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:30:"Matt: BuddyPress for the World";s:4:"guid";s:21:"http://ma.tt/?p=14098";s:4:"link";s:46:"http://ma.tt/2009/04/buddypress-for-the-world/";s:11:"description";s:867:"pHappy to announce that a href=http://buddypress.org/BuddyPress is now available to the world/a. BuddyPress is a package built on top of WordPress which transforms WP into a social network complete with profiles, friends, messaging, groups, and even activity streams. Of course it#8217;s 100% GPL and Open Source. It#8217;s built on top of MU (which can be tricky to install) so still not for everybody yet, but this is a major milestone in the WordPress world. a href=http://buddypress.org/Check it out/a. Congrats to Andy and the whole BuddyPress team. img src=http://ma.tt/blog/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif alt=:) class=wp-smiley /  a href=http://buddypress.org/blog/news/buddypress-10-has-arrivedHere#8217;s Andy#8217;s official  announcement post/a and a href=http://wordpress.org/development/2009/04/make-friends-with-buddypress/WordPress.org/a./p";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Thu, 30 Apr 2009 20:25:15 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:4:"Matt";}s:7:"summary";s:867:"pHappy to announce that a href=http://buddypress.org/BuddyPress is now available to the world/a. BuddyPress is a package built on top of WordPress which transforms WP into a social network complete with profiles, friends, messaging, groups, and even activity streams. Of course it#8217;s 100% GPL and Open Source. It#8217;s built on top of MU (which can be tricky to install) so still not for everybody yet, but this is a major milestone in the WordPress world. a href=http://buddypress.org/Check it out/a. Congrats to Andy and the whole BuddyPress team. img src=http://ma.tt/blog/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif alt=:) class=wp-smiley /  a href=http://buddypress.org/blog/news/buddypress-10-has-arrivedHere#8217;s Andy#8217;s official  announcement post/a and a href=http://wordpress.org/development/2009/04/make-friends-with-buddypress/WordPress.org/a./p";}i:20;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:38:"Dev Blog: Make Friends with BuddyPress";s:4:"guid";s:39:"http://wordpress.org/development/?p=719";s:4:"link";s:70:"http://wordpress.org/development/2009/04/make-friends-with-buddypress/";s:11:"description";s:1946:"pWhat if there was software with the elegance and extensibility of WordPress but all the features you#8217;ve come to expect from social networks like Facebook? Now there is: a href=http://buddypress.org/check out BuddyPress/a./p\npBuddyPress is an official sister project of WordPress. The idea behind it was to see what would happen to the web if it was as easy for anyone to create a social network as it is to create a blog today. There#8217;s been an explosion of social activity on the web, it#8217;s probably the most important trend of the past few years, but there#8217;s been a dearth of Open Source tools that enable the social web./p\npIn WordPress we have a robust and extensible base that can scale to many millions of users, and BuddyPress is essentially a set of plugins on top of WordPress that add private messaging, profiles, friends, groups, activity streams, and everything else you#8217;ve come to expect from your favorite social network, like a Facebook-in-a-box./p\npI don#8217;t think BuddyPress will be something you use eminstead of/em your existing social networks, I mean all your friends are already on Myspace, but if you wanted to start something new maybe with more control, friendlier terms of service, or just something customized and tweaked to fit exactly into your existing site, then BuddyPress is a great framework to use. Maybe even someday you#8217;ll be able to connect your BuddyPresses to each other and to the existing monolithic social networks./p\npThis is just a 1.0 release and it#8217;s not for everybody yet, for example it currently requires using MU which is a bit trickier to get set up than regular WordPress, but regardless a href=http://buddypress.org/I#8217;d recommend diving into the community at BuddyPress.org/a, which is great example of the software in action./p\npa href=http://buddypress.org/blog/news/buddypress-10-has-arrived/Here#8217;s Andy#8217;s official announcement post/a./p";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Thu, 30 Apr 2009 20:24:44 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:4:"Matt";}s:7:"summary";s:1946:"pWhat if there was software with the elegance and extensibility of WordPress but all the features you#8217;ve come to expect from social networks like Facebook? Now there is: a href=http://buddypress.org/check out BuddyPress/a./p\npBuddyPress is an official sister project of WordPress. The idea behind it was to see what would happen to the web if it was as easy for anyone to create a social network as it is to create a blog today. There#8217;s been an explosion of social activity on the web, it#8217;s probably the most important trend of the past few years, but there#8217;s been a dearth of Open Source tools that enable the social web./p\npIn WordPress we have a robust and extensible base that can scale to many millions of users, and BuddyPress is essentially a set of plugins on top of WordPress that add private messaging, profiles, friends, groups, activity streams, and everything else you#8217;ve come to expect from your favorite social network, like a Facebook-in-a-box./p\npI don#8217;t think BuddyPress will be something you use eminstead of/em your existing social networks, I mean all your friends are already on Myspace, but if you wanted to start something new maybe with more control, friendlier terms of service, or just something customized and tweaked to fit exactly into your existing site, then BuddyPress is a great framework to use. Maybe even someday you#8217;ll be able to connect your BuddyPresses to each other and to the existing monolithic social networks./p\npThis is just a 1.0 release and it#8217;s not for everybody yet, for example it currently requires using MU which is a bit trickier to get set up than regular WordPress, but regardless a href=http://buddypress.org/I#8217;d recommend diving into the community at BuddyPress.org/a, which is great example of the software in action./p\npa href=http://buddypress.org/blog/news/buddypress-10-has-arrived/Here#8217;s Andy#8217;s official announcement post/a./p";}i:21;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:38:"BuddyPress: BuddyPress 1.0 Has Arrived";s:4:"guid";s:28:"http://buddypress.org/?p=342";s:4:"link";s:58:"http://buddypress.org/blog/news/buddypress-10-has-arrived/";s:11:"description";s:12704:"pI#8217;m happy to announce that version 1.0 of a href=http://buddypress.org/aboutBuddyPress/a is now a href=http://buddypress.org/download/available for download/a./p\npThis release marks over a year of solid development, starting from the roots of the a href=http://chickspeak.com/ChickSpeak/a project, all the way to the blossoming developer community I see interacting on this site everyday./p\npThis is just the first step on a long road ahead. So much is possible now that we have a solid WordPress-based social framework to build upon./p\npThe status updates and gallery components are next on the roadmap, you can expect to see versions of those components appearing later this year. We#8217;ll also be going through the hundreds of enhancement tickets we#8217;ve received, and with your help prioritizing them for future versions./p\npI#8217;m most excited to see what plugin developers and theme designers can come up with. Even in the pre-release stages, a href=http://buddypress.org/extend/plugins/plugins/a to extend and add functionality have already been popping up. If you#8217;re a plugin developer or theme designer, be sure to check out the a href=http://codex.buddypress.org/how-to-guides/creating-a-custom-buddypress-component/skeleton component/a and a href=http://codex.buddypress.org/how-to-guides/creating-a-custom-buddypress-theme/skeleton theme/a. These packages will provide you with a solid starting point to build BuddyPress components and custom themes from./p\npI#8217;d also like to give some serious thanks to the community that has rallied around this project. I was told that getting people excited and involved with a new OSS project can be one of the hardest tasks to accomplish. I#8217;m really bowled over that so many people have become involved with BuddyPress development and feedback on a daily basis./p\npI#8217;d like to give a mention to every developer who has helped with the project, whether it be with tickets, advice, feedback or support:/p\npa href=http://buddypress.org/developers/adrenalisadrenalis/a, a href=http://buddypress.org/developers/ageeshkgageeshkg/a, a href=http://buddypress.org/developers/andyandy/a, a href=http://buddypress.org/developers/andrea_randrea_r/a, a href=http://buddypress.org/developers/arghagainarghagain/a, a href=http://buddypress.org/de