ugh ratio, then they will pay more per click.  You can optimize this click-through ratio by not displaying ads in situations where you know that they are not going to be clicked.  To do this, you have to realize that there are two types of visitors to your blog: new and returning.  New visitors are more likely to click on an advertisement than returning visitors so it is best if you do not show these ads to returning visitors at all./p\npYou can implement this feature by installing a href=http://planetozh.com/blog/my-projects/wordpress-plugin-who-sees-ads-control-adsense-display/Who Sees Ads?/a, which is the ultimate plugin for selectively displaying advertisments./p\npstrong7. Mini #8220;About#8221; section only for new visitors/strong/p\npHave you even been to a blog that as a mini #8220;About#8221; section in the sidebar? (If not, you can check out a href=http://planetozh.com/blog/Planet Ozh/a#8217;s sidebar)  Doesn#8217;t it make sense to show this section only to new visitors?  Hiding the section for returning visitors helps you reduce clutter in your sidebar and helps you bring other important content above the fold./p\npYou can also implement this using a href=http://planetozh.com/blog/my-projects/wordpress-plugin-who-sees-ads-control-adsense-display/Who Sees Ads?/a.  Just treat the #8220;About#8221; section as an ad unit in your sidebar and specify that it should only be displayed to new visitors./p\npstrong8. Ask for donations from returning visitors/strong/p\npTo me, it doesn#8217;t really make sense to ask a new visitor for donations because I#8217;m not sure how they feel about my content yet.  Now if the visitor returns quite often, then I know that my content is useful to them.  I am more comfortable asking regular readers for donations as they are more inclined to donate anyway.  To me, this feature implemented along with feature #6 makes a whole lot of sense.  New visitors only see ads and returning visitors only see donation requests./p\npYou can also implement this feature with a href=http://planetozh.com/blog/my-projects/wordpress-plugin-who-sees-ads-control-adsense-display/Who Sees Ads?/a.  Just treat the donate banner as an ad unit and specify that it should only be displayed to regular visitors./p\npstrong9. Display #8220;Out on Vacation#8221; message/strong/p\npEverybody needs to take a break once in a while.  Wouldn#8217;t it be nice to let your readers know that you are on vacation and let them know when to expect you back?  That way you don#8217;t lose readers from inactivity or lose readers who comment expecting an immediate reply./p\npThis is not really a feature based on visitor behavior, but I feel that it is still a smart feature because the message is only displayed to visitors that visit within a certain time period./p\npYou can again use a href=http://planetozh.com/blog/my-projects/wordpress-plugin-who-sees-ads-control-adsense-display/Who Sees Ads?/a to display an #8220;Out on Vacation#8221; message near the top of your blog between a specific date range.  I love this because when you come back from vacation, you won#8217;t have to remember to take down the notification banner.  You can also reuse the same notification banner the next time you go on vacation./p\nh3Conclusion/h3\npBy now, I think you guys get what I mean by a #8220;smart#8221; blog.  Hopefully, these powerful plugins can help you reshape your blog into a more visitor oriented blog./p\npGot a #8220;smart#8221; blog feature of your own?  Please share any other #8220;smart#8221; blog ideas in the comments section./p";}i:38;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:28:"Dev Blog: Design Tweaks Vote";s:4:"guid";s:39:"http://wordpress.org/development/?p=685";s:4:"link";s:60:"http://wordpress.org/development/2009/04/design-tweaks-vote/";s:11:"description";s:2553:"pComps for the header/nav design tweaks are in, and the results are mixed. Some people just moved a few things around, while others proposed a new style altogether. We won#8217;t make any major changes to style in 2.8, but if the vote leans toward a submission that proposes it, we#8217;ll do some user testing and make a decision for early 2.9 (which, now that we think of it, is probably the right thing to do anyway. img src=http://wordpress.org/development/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif alt=:) class=wp-smiley / )/p\npBelow are the links to the screenshots that were submitted. Please review each one (I#8217;d open them all in tabs so I could look back and forth while they are all large size, because the voting poll just uses thumbnails), then choose the one you think looks the best/is the most usable./p\npThis poll was supposed to close at 8pm NY time on Tuesday (today), but we#8217;re going to leave it open for an extra day. The voting poll will now be closed at 8pm NY time on Wednesday (that#8217;s 2am Thursday, UTC). If you want to discuss the entries#8217; pros/cons, a href=http://wordpress.org/support/topic/265261this thread/a would be a good place./p\npa href=http://wpdotorg.wordpress.com/files/2009/04/current.pngCurrent: The existing interface, for reference/a/p\npa href=http://p51labs.com/projects/wordpress-2.8-navigation/screenshot.pngKM: Current nav, header elements moved/a/p\npa href=http://andrerenaut.ovh.org/wp28.jpgAN: Current nav, file folder style header/a/p\npa href=http://konstruktors.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/mt-db-kaspars-dambis.pngKD: Current nav, modified header style/a/p\npa href=http://www.johnjamesjacoby.com/uploads/2009/04/jjj-wp-28.gifJJ: Swap blog title and favorites menu/a/p\npa href=http://deanjrobinson.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/mt-db-djr.pngDR1: Fluency style, dark/a/p\npa href=http://deanjrobinson.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/mt-db-djr-2.pngDR2: Fluency style, medium/a/p\npa href=http://deanjrobinson.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/mt-db-djr-3.pngDR3: Fluency style, light/a/p\npa href=http://wpdotorg.wordpress.com/files/2009/04/ik.pngIK: Nav layered over dark background/a/p\npa href=http://gordonbrander.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/mt-db-up.pngGB: Modified nav/header intersection/a/p\npa href=http://iammattthomas.com/28/dash.pngMT: Modified nav and header/a/p\npbr /\na href=http://answers.polldaddy.com/poll/1575922/Which style do you prefer?/aspan(a href=http://answers.polldaddy.comanswers/a)/spanbr /\n/p\npResults will be posted the day after the polls close. /p";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Tue, 28 Apr 2009 12:09:31 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:10:"Jane Wells";}s:7:"summary";s:2553:"pComps for the header/nav design tweaks are in, and the results are mixed. Some people just moved a few things around, while others proposed a new style altogether. We won#8217;t make any major changes to style in 2.8, but if the vote leans toward a submission that proposes it, we#8217;ll do some user testing and make a decision for early 2.9 (which, now that we think of it, is probably the right thing to do anyway. img src=http://wordpress.org/development/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif alt=:) class=wp-smiley / )/p\npBelow are the links to the screenshots that were submitted. Please review each one (I#8217;d open them all in tabs so I could look back and forth while they are all large size, because the voting poll just uses thumbnails), then choose the one you think looks the best/is the most usable./p\npThis poll was supposed to close at 8pm NY time on Tuesday (today), but we#8217;re going to leave it open for an extra day. The voting poll will now be closed at 8pm NY time on Wednesday (that#8217;s 2am Thursday, UTC). If you want to discuss the entries#8217; pros/cons, a href=http://wordpress.org/support/topic/265261this thread/a would be a good place./p\npa href=http://wpdotorg.wordpress.com/files/2009/04/current.pngCurrent: The existing interface, for reference/a/p\npa href=http://p51labs.com/projects/wordpress-2.8-navigation/screenshot.pngKM: Current nav, header elements moved/a/p\npa href=http://andrerenaut.ovh.org/wp28.jpgAN: Current nav, file folder style header/a/p\npa href=http://konstruktors.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/mt-db-kaspars-dambis.pngKD: Current nav, modified header style/a/p\npa href=http://www.johnjamesjacoby.com/uploads/2009/04/jjj-wp-28.gifJJ: Swap blog title and favorites menu/a/p\npa href=http://deanjrobinson.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/mt-db-djr.pngDR1: Fluency style, dark/a/p\npa href=http://deanjrobinson.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/mt-db-djr-2.pngDR2: Fluency style, medium/a/p\npa href=http://deanjrobinson.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/mt-db-djr-3.pngDR3: Fluency style, light/a/p\npa href=http://wpdotorg.wordpress.com/files/2009/04/ik.pngIK: Nav layered over dark background/a/p\npa href=http://gordonbrander.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/mt-db-up.pngGB: Modified nav/header intersection/a/p\npa href=http://iammattthomas.com/28/dash.pngMT: Modified nav and header/a/p\npbr /\na href=http://answers.polldaddy.com/poll/1575922/Which style do you prefer?/aspan(a href=http://answers.polldaddy.comanswers/a)/spanbr /\n/p\npResults will be posted the day after the polls close. /p";}i:39;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:14:"Matt: Spam SEO";s:4:"guid";s:21:"http://ma.tt/?p=14096";s:4:"link";s:30:"http://ma.tt/2009/04/spam-seo/";s:11:"description";s:105:"pa href=http://blog.akismet.com/2009/04/28/eliminating-spam-is-good-seo/Eliminating spam is good SEO/a./p";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Tue, 28 Apr 2009 08:16:30 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:4:"Matt";}s:7:"summary";s:105:"pa href=http://blog.akismet.com/2009/04/28/eliminating-spam-is-good-seo/Eliminating spam is good SEO/a./p";}i:40;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:37:"Akismet: Eliminating spam is good SEO";s:4:"guid";s:30:"http://blog.akismet.com/?p=157";s:4:"link";s:64:"http://blog.akismet.com/2009/04/28/eliminating-spam-is-good-seo/";s:11:"description";s:6543:"div class=snap_previewbr /pOne of the most common forms of comment and pingback spam right now is the relatively subtle, ambiguous kind #8212; short phrases or questions that are not obviously spam, at least on face value.  Since we a href=http://blog.akismet.com/2007/11/27/it-really-is-spam/last posted about this/a, the more sophisticated spammers have progressed from old standbys like #8220;nice post#8221; and #8220;great blog#8221;, to more cunning things like questions (#8221;where can I download your theme?#8221;) and appeals to your helpful nature (#8221;I#8217;m having trouble subscribing to your RSS feed#8221;)./p\npAkismet almost always catches these kinds of bogus comments./p\npThe tip-off of course is that they often include a link to a site that#8217;s advertising dubious or sleazy merchandise (or worse, a web site that harms the viewer#8217;s computer).  But it#8217;s easy to forget to look at the link before approving a comment, or give the comment author the benefit of the doubt without checking closely.  And spammers have recently learned to post several comments over time, the first of which contains no link or obvious clue.  (We call these emprecursor spams/em)./p\npAnyway, a comment is a comment, right, so what#8217;s the harm in approving a few tame platitudes, even if they were posted by spammers?/p\npUnfortunately it emis/em harmful, and most of the damage is emto your own site/em./p\npBy moving these comments out of your spam folder and publishing them on your blog, you#8217;re doing three things, all of them bad:/p\npstrong1. You are undermining your site#8217;s SEO./strong/p\npThe spammer#8217;s web site might seem inoffensive on face value.  But the black-hat SEO and spam methods used by its promoter are not. That same spammer is busy building backlinks from anywhere they can find them, including some of the web#8217;s worst neighbourhoods.  By regularly publishing links to spammers#8217; web sites, you#8217;re giving Google and other search engines a hint that links from your blog are poor quality./p\npNow it#8217;s true that Google will emtry/em not to penalize a web site for inadvertently linking to a a href=http://www.google.com/support/webmasters/bin/answer.py?hl=enamp;answer=35769#3bad neighbourhood/a.  But even if they don#8217;t, you are weakening the value of each of the other links from your blog - #8220;diluting your GoogleJuice#8221;, if you like - and helping to validate the spammer#8217;s web site.  In some cases you might even find that emyou are helping the spammer overtake your blog in search engine results/em./p\npstrong2. You are attracting more spammers./strong/p\npLess skilled spammers will deliberately emseek out blogs that other spammers have successfully spammed/em, because they know they are easy targets.  Organized spammers circulate lists of such blogs (for a small fee of course).  And professionals keep their own lists of previous victims, because they know future spam is even more likely to be approved there.  By letting some spam through - even seemingly harmless ones - you are providing a signal to spammers that your blog is a profitable target.  (Experienced bloggers will be familiar with this phenomenon: you accidentally approve one seemingly unremarkable spam comment, and a big batch of ugly spam follows soon after)./p\npWordPress and many other blog applications have a feature, independent of Akismet, where regular users who have had at least one comment approved, will automatically skip the moderation queue next time and have their comments published right away.  Spammers know this, and they#8217;ll come back to take advantage of it.  Often they#8217;ll link to a harmless looking site in their first comment (or include no link at all), but link to progressively more blatant spam in subsequent comments./p\npstrong3. You are damaging your reputation./strong/p\npYou might not click on the links in all the comments on your blog, but some of your readers will.  And some of those links will go to sites that are sleazy, offensive, or harmful./p\npWorse still, a spam tactic that is becoming more popular is to first post a small number of spam comments on innocent blogs; then send a large volume of spam to other web sites linking to the blog post that contains those comments.  (They do this to try to get around spam filters and blacklist that recognize and catch links to their own site)./p\npIf you do publish spam comments on your blog, you might discover later that thousands of other blogs and forums have been spammed with emlinks to your blog/em./p\npSo what should you do about it?/p\npAkismet will almost always catch these comments and put them in your Spam folder.  Usually you don#8217;t need to do anything; just don#8217;t approve them for publication./p\npWe have a real-time view of spam activity on millions of blogs around the world, so we can detect empatterns in behaviour/em that can#8217;t be seen by looking at any one single comment.  If a bland, generic comment turns up in your spam folder, you should be suspicious of it - Akismet flagged it for a reason.  Think twice before approving it for publication.  Unless you know the author, it almost certainly emis/em spam #8212; or a subtle precursor to it./p\npAlso, keep an eye out for forthcoming Akismet updates.  In addition to our usual work behind the scenes monitoring and adapting to new spam techniques, we#8217;re developing some new features designed specifically to help protect against the potential harm done by spammers./p\n  a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/akismet.wordpress.com/157/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/akismet.wordpress.com/157/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godelicious/akismet.wordpress.com/157/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/delicious/akismet.wordpress.com/157/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gostumble/akismet.wordpress.com/157/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/stumble/akismet.wordpress.com/157/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godigg/akismet.wordpress.com/157/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpres