 time and have their comments published right away.  Spammers know this, and they#8217;ll come back to take advantage of it.  Often they#8217;ll link to a harmless looking site in their first comment (or include no link at all), but link to progressively more blatant spam in subsequent comments./p\npstrong3. You are damaging your reputation./strong/p\npYou might not click on the links in all the comments on your blog, but some of your readers will.  And some of those links will go to sites that are sleazy, offensive, or harmful./p\npWorse still, a spam tactic that is becoming more popular is to first post a small number of spam comments on innocent blogs; then send a large volume of spam to other web sites linking to the blog post that contains those comments.  (They do this to try to get around spam filters and blacklist that recognize and catch links to their own site)./p\npIf you do publish spam comments on your blog, you might discover later that thousands of other blogs and forums have been spammed with emlinks to your blog/em./p\npSo what should you do about it?/p\npAkismet will almost always catch these comments and put them in your Spam folder.  Usually you don#8217;t need to do anything; just don#8217;t approve them for publication./p\npWe have a real-time view of spam activity on millions of blogs around the world, so we can detect empatterns in behaviour/em that can#8217;t be seen by looking at any one single comment.  If a bland, generic comment turns up in your spam folder, you should be suspicious of it - Akismet flagged it for a reason.  Think twice before approving it for publication.  Unless you know the author, it almost certainly emis/em spam #8212; or a subtle precursor to it./p\npAlso, keep an eye out for forthcoming Akismet updates.  In addition to our usual work behind the scenes monitoring and adapting to new spam techniques, we#8217;re developing some new features designed specifically to help protect against the potential harm done by spammers./p\n  a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/akismet.wordpress.com/157/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/akismet.wordpress.com/157/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godelicious/akismet.wordpress.com/157/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/delicious/akismet.wordpress.com/157/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gostumble/akismet.wordpress.com/157/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/stumble/akismet.wordpress.com/157/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godigg/akismet.wordpress.com/157/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/digg/akismet.wordpress.com/157/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/goreddit/akismet.wordpress.com/157/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/reddit/akismet.wordpress.com/157/ //a img alt= border=0 src=http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=blog.akismet.comblog=116920post=157subd=akismetref=feed=1 //div";}i:41;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:37:"WordPress.tv: WordPress.tv is hiring!";s:4:"guid";s:30:"http://blog.wordpress.tv/?p=58";s:4:"link";s:58:"http://blog.wordpress.tv/2009/04/28/wordpresstv-is-hiring/";s:11:"description";s:3987:"div class=snap_previewbr /pstrongI#8217;m super-excited to say that we#8217;re hiring here at WordPress.tv towers!/strong/p\npWith our combined focus on community content and putting out fresh tutorials for you, there are only so many hours a day in the average week. So, to make sure that we cover the gamut of WordPress video, we#8217;re going to need an extra pair of hands./p\npYou can find the job description at our a href=http://automattic.com/jobs/Automattic jobs page/a - the job you#8217;re looking at is the #8220;Reel Wrangler#8221;. Here are a few more details:/p\npspan id=more-58/span/p\npstrongAre you our Reel Wrangling WPTVist?/strong/p\npThe job calls for a flexible, creative jack or jill of all trades with an independent mind. Here at the Automattic ranch we all work from home, manage our own workloads, and live free of micro-management and rigid hierarchy. Laughing at Matt#8217;s jokes is optional, although it does win you first dibs at the BBQ./p\npThat means you need to be able to communicate what#8217;s happening, what needs fixing, and what you think, through our variety of online meeting places./p\npstrongWith this position you#8217;ll be:/strong/p\np*Engaging with the WordPress community, and the videomakers within it - from scouting talent to uploading and publishing awesome videos from around the world/p\np*Actively moderating the WordPress.tv community, and helping people to find the help they need/p\np*Pinging out updates, blog posts, tweets and suchlike/p\np*Making our content more accessible with subtitle transcriptions/p\np*Managing our incoming videos, checking them out, and publishing the best to the web/p\np*Potentially helping out a bit with some concise, straight to the point screencasts/p\np*Sharing your thoughts, progress and whatever else blow-by-blow on the live-to-the-world a href=http://dev.wordpress.tvWordPress.tv dev blog/a/p\np*Working with a person whose eyebrows outsize even Sylar#8217;s/p\npstrongYou#8217;ll need to be:/strong/p\np*Easy to get along with, patient and kind (yes, just like Mary Poppins)/p\np*WordPress, HTML and CSS savvy (as in working knowledge rather than genius, although that won#8217;t hurt)/p\np*Familiar with video formats, publishing media to the web and using FTP/p\np*Self-motivated, independent and focused on making cool stuff happen/p\np*Bonus points for any screencasting, documentation or community/support chops/p\npstrongWe can#8217;t wait to hear from you/strong - to apply, you#8217;ll want to a href=http://automattic.com/jobs/check out all of the details here/a, or if you#8217;re super-confident, send a *short* email and your resumé to jobs [at] automattic [dot] [com]. We#8217;d rather you didn#8217;t apply in the comments or via the WordPress.tv contact form, and doing so will earn you 10 Suck-Points for not having read this img src=http://s.wordpress.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif alt=:) class=wp-smiley / /p\npLooking forward to hearing from you!/p\n  a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godelicious/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/delicious/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gostumble/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/stumble/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godigg/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/digg/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/goreddit/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/reddit/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/ //a img alt= border=0 src=http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=blog.wordpress.tvblog=5310177post=58subd=wptvblogref=feed=1 //div";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Tue, 28 Apr 2009 03:45:25 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:12:"Michael Pick";}s:7:"summary";s:3987:"div class=snap_previewbr /pstrongI#8217;m super-excited to say that we#8217;re hiring here at WordPress.tv towers!/strong/p\npWith our combined focus on community content and putting out fresh tutorials for you, there are only so many hours a day in the average week. So, to make sure that we cover the gamut of WordPress video, we#8217;re going to need an extra pair of hands./p\npYou can find the job description at our a href=http://automattic.com/jobs/Automattic jobs page/a - the job you#8217;re looking at is the #8220;Reel Wrangler#8221;. Here are a few more details:/p\npspan id=more-58/span/p\npstrongAre you our Reel Wrangling WPTVist?/strong/p\npThe job calls for a flexible, creative jack or jill of all trades with an independent mind. Here at the Automattic ranch we all work from home, manage our own workloads, and live free of micro-management and rigid hierarchy. Laughing at Matt#8217;s jokes is optional, although it does win you first dibs at the BBQ./p\npThat means you need to be able to communicate what#8217;s happening, what needs fixing, and what you think, through our variety of online meeting places./p\npstrongWith this position you#8217;ll be:/strong/p\np*Engaging with the WordPress community, and the videomakers within it - from scouting talent to uploading and publishing awesome videos from around the world/p\np*Actively moderating the WordPress.tv community, and helping people to find the help they need/p\np*Pinging out updates, blog posts, tweets and suchlike/p\np*Making our content more accessible with subtitle transcriptions/p\np*Managing our incoming videos, checking them out, and publishing the best to the web/p\np*Potentially helping out a bit with some concise, straight to the point screencasts/p\np*Sharing your thoughts, progress and whatever else blow-by-blow on the live-to-the-world a href=http://dev.wordpress.tvWordPress.tv dev blog/a/p\np*Working with a person whose eyebrows outsize even Sylar#8217;s/p\npstrongYou#8217;ll need to be:/strong/p\np*Easy to get along with, patient and kind (yes, just like Mary Poppins)/p\np*WordPress, HTML and CSS savvy (as in working knowledge rather than genius, although that won#8217;t hurt)/p\np*Familiar with video formats, publishing media to the web and using FTP/p\np*Self-motivated, independent and focused on making cool stuff happen/p\np*Bonus points for any screencasting, documentation or community/support chops/p\npstrongWe can#8217;t wait to hear from you/strong - to apply, you#8217;ll want to a href=http://automattic.com/jobs/check out all of the details here/a, or if you#8217;re super-confident, send a *short* email and your resumé to jobs [at] automattic [dot] [com]. We#8217;d rather you didn#8217;t apply in the comments or via the WordPress.tv contact form, and doing so will earn you 10 Suck-Points for not having read this img src=http://s.wordpress.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif alt=:) class=wp-smiley / /p\npLooking forward to hearing from you!/p\n  a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godelicious/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/delicious/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gostumble/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/stumble/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godigg/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/digg/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/goreddit/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/reddit/wptvblog.wordpress.com/58/ //a img alt= border=0 src=http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=blog.wordpress.tvblog=5310177post=58subd=wptvblogref=feed=1 //div";}i:42;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:60:"Weblog Tools Collection: WordPress Plugin Releases for 04/27";s:4:"guid";s:40:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/?p=5701";s:4:"link";s:88:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2009/04/27/wordpress-plugin-releases-for-0427/";s:11:"description";s:3148:"h3New Plugins/h3\npa href=http://coffee2code.com/wp-plugins/expandable-dashboard-recent-commentsExpandable Dashboard Recent Comments/a/p\npAdds the ability to do an in-place expansion of comment excerpts on the admin dashboard ‘Recent Comments’ widget./p\npa href=http://johnhawkinsunrated.com/wordpress-pluginsAds for Old Posts/a/p\npThe Ads For Old Posts plugin will automatically insert an ad block in your posts once they reach a certain age. The idea is to not bother your regular readers with ads, but display the ads for people who may find your posts months and years later./p\npa href=http://www.seo-traffic-guide.de/wp-cartoon/WP Cartoon/a/p\npThis plugin lets you integrate the daily web cartoon from a href=http://www.danscartoons.com/http://www.danscartoons.com//a for non-commercial websites. It adds a button to the TinyMCE Editor in your wordpress installation so that you can integrate the cartoon with one click on any page or post you like./p\npa href=http://themesphere.com/twitter-counter-wordpress-plugin.htmlTwounter/a/p\npTwounter is a WordPress Plugin that fetches the number of followers for a twitter profile and returns it in plain text format. Twounter uses Twitter API to ensure that the plugin provides the maximum speed while fetching the number of followers./p\npa href=http://www.ifgogo.com/323/wordpress-comment-digg-plugin/WordPress Comment Digg/a/p\npThis plugin will allow users to digg / bury every thread of your comments, thus find out the most valuable comments as well as the human-spammers./p\npa href=http://admiyn.com/admiyn-twitter.htmlAdmiyn Twitter/a/p\npAdmiyn Twitter is simple and useful way to change your Twitter#8217;s status whenever a new post or comment is published in your blog./p\nh3Updated Plugins/h3\npa href=http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/add-to-any/Add to Any/a/p\npAllows your visitors to submit posts to various sites/p\npa href=http://www.gdstarrating.com/2009/04/22/gd-star-rating-120/GD Star Rating/a/p\npGD Star Rating is post, page and comment rating plugin for WordPress. Plugin supports different image sets, rating moderation, vote rules, time restricted voting, templates, trend calculations, multi ratings, templated rendering, has a widgets build in and extensive shortcode support./p\npa href=http://omninoggin.com/wordpress-plugins/wp-minify-wordpress-plugin/WP Minify/a/p\npThis plugin helps you easily integrate the Minify engine into your WordPress blog. Once enabled, this plugin will combine and compress JS and files enqueued by wp_enqueue_script() and wp_enqueue_style() to improve page load time./p\npa href=http://omninoggin.com/wordpress-plugins/wp-greet-box-wordpress-plugin/WP Greet Box/a/p\npThis plugin lets you show a different greeting message to your new visitors depending on their referrer url./p\npa href=http://sww.co.nz/wordpress-plugins/ezy-nav-menu/Ezy Nav Menu/a/p\npMakes use of WP#8217;s built in #8216;Edit Links#8217; to create and manage a website navigation menu that can be displayed using a custom template tag./p\npa href=http://ideasilo.wordpress.com/2009/04/23/contact-form-7-1951/Contact Form 7/a/p\npAn easy method to allow users to contact you/p";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Mon, 27 Apr 2009 20:24:44 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:7:"Perurry";}s:7:"summary";s:3148:"h3New Plugins/h3\npa href=http://coffee2code.com/wp-plugins/expandable-dashboard-recent-commentsExpandable Dashboard Recent Comments/a/p\npAdds the ability to do an in-place expansion of comment excerpts on the admin dashboard ‘Recent Comments’ widget./p\npa href=http://johnhawkinsunrated.com/wordpress-pluginsAds for Old Posts/a/p\npThe Ads For Old Posts plugin will automatically insert an ad block in your posts once they reach a certain age. The idea is to not bother your regular readers with ads, but display the ads for people who may find your posts months and years later./p\npa href=http://www.seo-traffic-guide.de/wp-cartoon/WP Cartoon/a/p\npThis plugin lets you integrate the daily web cartoon from a href=http://www.danscartoons.com/http://www.danscartoons.com//a for non-commercial websites. It adds a button to the TinyMCE Editor in your wordpress installation so that you can integrate the cartoon with one click on any page or post you like./p\npa href=http://themesphere.com/twitter-counter-wordpress-plugin.htmlTwounter/a/p\npTwounter is a WordPress Plugin that fetches the number of followers for a twitter profile and returns it in plain text format. Twounter uses Twitter API to ensure that the plugin provides the maximum speed while fetching the number of followers./p\npa href=http://www.ifgogo.com/323/wordpress-comment-digg-plugin/WordPress Comment Digg/a/p\npThis plugin will allow users to digg / bury every thread of your comments, thus find out the most valuable comments as well as the human-spammers./p\npa href=http://admiyn.com/admiyn-twitter.htmlAdmiyn Twitter/a/p\npAdmiyn Twitter is simple and useful way to change your Twitter#8217;s status whenever a new post or comment is published in your blog./p\nh3Updated Plugins/h3\npa href=http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/add-to-any/Add to Any/a/p\npAllows your visitors to submit posts to various sites/p\npa href=http://www.gdstarrating.com/2009/04/22/gd-star-rating-120/GD Star Rating/a/p\npGD Star Rating is post, page and comment rating plugin for WordPress. Plugin supports different image sets, rating moderation, vote rules, time restricted voting, templates, trend calculations, multi ratings, templated rendering, has a widgets build in and extensive shortcode support./p\npa href=http://omninoggin.com/wordpress-plugins/wp-minify-wordpress-plugin/WP Minify/a/p\npThis plugin helps you easily integrate the Minify engine into your WordPress blog. Once enabled, this plugin will combine and compress JS and files enqueued by wp_enqueue_script() and wp_enqueue_style() to improve page load time./p\npa href=http://omninoggin.com/wordpress-plugins/wp-greet-box-wordpress-plugin/WP Greet Box/a/p\npThis plugin lets you show a different greeting message to your new visitors depending on their referrer url./p\npa href=http://sww.co.nz/wordpress-plugins/ezy-nav-menu/Ezy Nav Menu/a/p\npMakes use of WP#8217;s built in #8216;Edit Links#8217; to create and manage a website navigation menu that can be displayed using a custom template tag./p\npa href=http://ideasilo.wordpress.com/2009/04/23/contact-form-7-1951/Contact Form 7/a/p\npAn easy method to allow users to contact you/p";}i:43;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:28:"Matt: Wired Joins the Family";s:4:"guid";s:21:"http://ma.tt/?p=14093";s:4:"link";s:44:"http://ma.tt/2009/04/wired-joins-the-family/";s:11:"description";s:765:"pI wanted to take a moment to welcome a href=http://www.wired.com/blogs/Wired.com#8217;s 12 blogs/a to the WordPress family! (They just completed their switch from a href=http://www.typepad.com/Typepad/a.) I thought this completes a href=http://ma.tt/2009/01/top-100-blogs/my prediction from January/a that WP would reach over a href=http://royal.pingdom.com/2009/01/15/the-blog-platforms-of-choice-among-the-top-100-blogs/40% of this list of top blogs/a, but when I went to the a href=http://technorati.com/pop/blogs/Technorati 100/a today everything has changed! First, they only show ten blogs at a time now (lame!) and second there appears to have been huge churn on the list,so we#8217;ll have to wait until next January to do an apples-to-apples comparison./p";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Mon, 27 Apr 2009 18:22:15 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:4:"Matt";}s:7:"summary";s:765:"pI wanted to take a moment to welcome a href=http://www.wired.com/blogs/Wired.com#8217;s 12 blogs/a to the WordPress family! (They just completed their switch from a href=http://www.typepad.com/Typepad/a.) I thought this completes a href=http://ma.tt/2009/01/top-100-blogs/my prediction from January/a that WP would reach over a href=http://royal.pingdom.com/2009/01/15/the-blog-platforms-of-choice-among-the-top-100-blogs/40% of this list of top blogs/a, but when I went to the a href=http://technorati.com/pop/blogs/Technorati 100/a today everything has changed! First, they only show ten blogs at a time now (lame!) and second there appears to have been huge churn on the list,so we#8217;ll have to wait until next January to do an apples-to-apples comparison./p";}i:44;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:62:"WordPress.tv: Feeds glorious feeds - WordPress.tv to your door";s:4:"guid";s:30:"http://blog.wordpress.tv/?p=49";s:4:"link";s:82:"http://blog.wordpress.tv/2009/04/27/feeds-glorious-feeds-wordpresstv-to-your-door/";s:11:"description";s:2508:"div class=snap_previewbr /pstrongWe#8217;ve been working behind the scenes to make it easier for you to watch WordPress.tv/strong tutorials wherever you are - online or off./p\npSo you#8217;ll notice now that on the a href=http://wordpress.tvfront page of WordPress.tv/a  (scroll down to the bottom) you can click to subscribe to our videos via the awesome, cross-platform, Open Source media center a href=http://getmiro.comMiro/a. If you haven#8217;t checked out Miro, yet, it#8217;s an excellent way to download, watch, sort and browse web video, video podcasts, and even the video files on your computer. Better still, it#8217;s totally Open, free to use, runs on pretty much any computer out there (although if you have a 10 year old system it might struggle with HD) and even brings you YouTube and other web-based video in glorious full-screen HD (source files allowing)./p\npWe#8217;re big fans, if you haven#8217;t guessed./p\npYou can also subscribe to WordPress.tv in your feed reader of choice, or iTunes, via the feed URL a href=http://wordpress.tv/feedhttp://wordpress.tv/feed/a/p\npIn iTunes, head to Advanced -gt; Subscribe to Podcast, and drop in the URL above. You#8217;ll be good to go and can then download any videos that tickle your fancy. /p\npWe#8217;re still working out a few kinks, but if you#8217;re anxious to get your hands on our free (as in beer, as in freedom) tutorials in iPod-friendly MP4 format - you now have a bunch of ways you can do so./p\npEnjoy!/p\n  a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godelicious/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/delicious/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gostumble/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/stumble/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godigg/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/digg/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/goreddit/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/reddit/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/ //a img alt= border=0 src=http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=blog.wordpress.tvblog=5310177post=49subd=wptvblogref=feed=1 //div";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Mon, 27 Apr 2009 08:45:18 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:12:"Michael Pick";}s:7:"summary";s:2508:"div class=snap_previewbr /pstrongWe#8217;ve been working behind the scenes to make it easier for you to watch WordPress.tv/strong tutorials wherever you are - online or off./p\npSo you#8217;ll notice now that on the a href=http://wordpress.tvfront page of WordPress.tv/a  (scroll down to the bottom) you can click to subscribe to our videos via the awesome, cross-platform, Open Source media center a href=http://getmiro.comMiro/a. If you haven#8217;t checked out Miro, yet, it#8217;s an excellent way to download, watch, sort and browse web video, video podcasts, and even the video files on your computer. Better still, it#8217;s totally Open, free to use, runs on pretty much any computer out there (although if you have a 10 year old system it might struggle with HD) and even brings you YouTube and other web-based video in glorious full-screen HD (source files allowing)./p\npWe#8217;re big fans, if you haven#8217;t guessed./p\npYou can also subscribe to WordPress.tv in your feed reader of choice, or iTunes, via the feed URL a href=http://wordpress.tv/feedhttp://wordpress.tv/feed/a/p\npIn iTunes, head to Advanced -gt; Subscribe to Podcast, and drop in the URL above. You#8217;ll be good to go and can then download any videos that tickle your fancy. /p\npWe#8217;re still working out a few kinks, but if you#8217;re anxious to get your hands on our free (as in beer, as in freedom) tutorials in iPod-friendly MP4 format - you now have a bunch of ways you can do so./p\npEnjoy!/p\n  a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godelicious/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/delicious/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gostumble/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/stumble/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godigg/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/digg/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/ //a a rel=nofollow href=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/goreddit/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/img alt= border=0 src=http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/reddit/wptvblog.wordpress.com/49/ //a img alt= border=0 src=http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=blog.wordpress.tvblog=5310177post=49subd=wptvblogref=feed=1 //div";}i:45;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:52:"Weblog Tools Collection: The Hidden Gem Of WordPress";s:4:"guid";s:40:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/?p=5697";s:4:"link";s:81:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2009/04/27/the-hiddem-gem-of-wordpress/";s:11:"description";s:1793:"pThe other day, I was thinking about how easy it is to make a mess on the web. For example, purchasing a domain that you attach an email address to that is used for a year only to end up wanting to use a different domain. This means you have to go to every site you registered an account with and change the email address if you plan on letting the old domain retire. There are also a host of other issues as well which in the end, just seems like a giant mess. For this reason alone, I believe hosted blogging solutions will always have a market because you don#8217;t have to worry about moving around or managing a domain. Typically, all you have to do is register an account and blog. /p\npHowever, users of WordPress.com have an awesome benefit that not many other blog hosting providers can match and that is, a free, open-source project based on much of the same code that powers the hosted service. It#8217;s very unlikely but if WordPress.com were to ever go out of business, using WXR or a href=http://codex.wordpress.org/Administration_Panels#Import target=_blankWordPress Extended RSS/a you could export your content from your hosted account and move it to a self-hosted install of WordPress without missing a beat. If we look into the past, Matt has made it clear that WordPress will exist as an open-source project for as long as he is alive and hopefully, long after he is gone. Talk about peace of mind./p\npThere are a couple of blog host providers which are making some noise in the market right now and even though some of them provide a fancy way of doing things, I prefer having the control over the fate of my content rather than a fancy interface for blogging. /p\npbHow important is the export/import of data when it comes to choosing a blog host or blogging software?/b/p";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Mon, 27 Apr 2009 08:25:08 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:13:"Jeff Chandler";}s:7:"summary";s:1793:"pThe other day, I was thinking about how easy it is to make a mess on the web. For example, purchasing a domain that you attach an email address to that is used for a year only to end up wanting to use a different domain. This means you have to go to every site you registered an account with and change the email address if you plan on letting the old domain retire. There are also a host of other issues as well which in the end, just seems like a giant mess. For this reason alone, I believe hosted blogging solutions will always have a market because you don#8217;t have to worry about moving around or managing a domain. Typically, all you have to do is register an account and blog. /p\npHowever, users of WordPress.com have an awesome benefit that not many other blog hosting providers can match and that is, a free, open-source project based on much of the same code that powers the hosted service. It#8217;s very unlikely but if WordPress.com were to ever go out of business, using WXR or a href=http://codex.wordpress.org/Administration_Panels#Import target=_blankWordPress Extended RSS/a you could export your content from your hosted account and move it to a self-hosted install of WordPress without missing a beat. If we look into the past, Matt has made it clear that WordPress will exist as an open-source project for as long as he is alive and hopefully, long after he is gone. Talk about peace of mind./p\npThere are a couple of blog host providers which are making some noise in the market right now and even though some of them provide a fancy way of doing things, I prefer having the control over the fate of my content rather than a fancy interface for blogging. /p\npbHow important is the export/import of data when it comes to choosing a blog host or blogging software?/b/p";}i:46;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:75:"Weblog Tools Collection: Announcing Wordpress Plugin Competition 2009 (3.0)";s:4:"guid";s:40:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/?p=5695";s:4:"link";s:101:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2009/04/26/announcing-wordpress-plugin-competition-2009-30/";s:11:"description";s:4015:"pIt is that time of the year again. We will be holding another a href=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/pluginblogWordPress Plugin Competition/a. The Plugin Competitions held in the past years have generated a tremendous amount of interest in WordPress and our entrants have come up with fantastic plugins such as a href=http://pressography.com/plugins/wp-comment-remix/WP Comment Remix/a, a href=http://www.aaronharp.com/dev/wp-manageable/Manageable/a,  a href=http://planetozh.com/blog/my-projects/wordpress-plugin-who-sees-ads-control-adsense-display/Who Sees Ads/a and of course a href=http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dc2rmw69_302c8tvhhnOneClick/a in addition to hundreds of others that were voted upon by readers like you. We have distributed thousands of dollars in prizes, helped popularize hundreds of plugins and have even prompted the adoption of various peices of code into the WordPress core. With a href=http://wordpress.org/development/2009/04/has-patch-marathon-results/WordPress 2.8 around the bend/a and the a href=http://wordpress.org/development/2009/04/summer-of-code-students-announced/Google Summer of Code/a, I have very high hopes for this year. Here are some links for those that have not yet participated or looked into our past WordPress Plugin Competitions:/p\nul\nlia href=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2008/09/13/wordpress-plugin-competition-25-winners/WordPress Plugin Competition 2008 Winners/a/li\nlia href=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2007/08/26/winners-wordpress-plugin-competition/WordPress Plugin Competition 2007 Winners/a/li\nlia href=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2005/07/23/wordpress-plugin-competition-winners/WordPress Plugin Competition 2005 Winners/a/li\nlia href=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/pluginblogWordPress Plugin Competition Blog/a/li\nlia href=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/plugin-competition-prizes/List of prizes from last year/a/li\n/ul\npstrongWe are looking for donations (via Paypal) towards the final purse for this years#8217; competition. WeblogToolsCollection pledges $1000 towards the final prizes. /strong/p\npWe will not be removing the past entries from the Plugin Competition blog. Much of the rules and expectations remain the same. They are listed below. The plugins will be judged by a panel of emat least/em three judges. strong/strong/p\npSome relevant details:/p\nul\nlistrongAll code emmust/em be GstrongPL/strong/strongstrong compatible/strong/li\nlistrongAll Plugins must be compatible with WordPress 2.7 and above/strong/li\nlistrongAll Plugins have to be secure and use secure coding methods. This is very important.br /\n/strong/li\nliPlugins must be made available through the a href=http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/Wordpress Extend pages/a/li\nliPlugins must be officially submitted through email and announced and discussed on the a href=http://feeds2.feedburner.com/pluginblog/Plugin Competition Blog/a. More details on submissions will be added in the last month of the competition. Release of plugin after competition start does not mean submission. You can submit your plugin way after its release to work out bugs etc./li\nliRunning time for competition = 3 months starting the 1st of May till the 31st of July/li\nliTrue Wordpress plugins only. No manual modifications can be required of users. No editing of core files allowed./li\nliYou cannot submit plugins that have been released already. Modification or re-use of existing code to achieve completely new functionality allowed./li\nliAll plugins require documentation as in the a href=http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/about/faq/Wordpress Extend pages/a./li\nliPreliminary support for the plugin has to be provided to the public./li\nliAny and all prizes/controversies/issues will be judged and decided at my sole discretion./li\nliPast winners are not eligible for this competition./li\n/ul\npPlease let us know if we can help answer any questions or if you would like to donate some money to the competition prizes. Your help will go a long way./p";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sun, 26 Apr 2009 22:08:34 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:10:"Mark Ghosh";}s:7:"summary";s:4015:"pIt is that time of the year again. We will be holding another a href=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/pluginblogWordPress Plugin Competition/a. The Plugin Competitions held in the past years have generated a tremendous amount of interest in WordPress and our entrants have come up with fantastic plugins such as a href=http://pressography.com/plugins/wp-comment-remix/WP Comment Remix/a, a href=http://www.aaronharp.com/dev/wp-manageable/Manageable/a,  a href=http://planetozh.com/blog/my-projects/wordpress-plugin-who-sees-ads-control-adsense-display/Who Sees Ads/a and of course a href=http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dc2rmw69_302c8tvhhnOneClick/a in addition to hundreds of others that were voted upon by readers like you. We have distributed thousands of dollars in prizes, helped popularize hundreds of plugins and have even prompted the adoption of various peices of code into the WordPress core. With a href=http://wordpress.org/development/2009/04/has-patch-marathon-results/WordPress 2.8 around the bend/a and the a href=http://wordpress.org/development/2009/04/summer-of-code-students-announced/Google Summer of Code/a, I have very high hopes for this year. Here are some links for those that have not yet participated or looked into our past WordPress Plugin Competitions:/p\nul\nlia href=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2008/09/13/wordpress-plugin-competition-25-winners/WordPress Plugin Competition 2008 Winners/a/li\nlia href=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2007/08/26/winners-wordpress-plugin-competition/WordPress Plugin Competition 2007 Winners/a/li\nlia href=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/archives/2005/07/23/wordpress-plugin-competition-winners/WordPress Plugin Competition 2005 Winners/a/li\nlia href=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/pluginblogWordPress Plugin Competition Blog/a/li\nlia href=http://weblogtoolscollection.com/plugin-competition-prizes/List of prizes from last year/a/li\n/ul\npstrongWe are looking for donations (via Paypal) towards the final purse for this years#8217; competition. WeblogToolsCollection pledges $1000 towards the final prizes. /strong/p\npWe will not be removing the past entries from the Plugin Competition blog. Much of the rules and expectations remain the same. They are listed below. The plugins will be judged by a panel of emat least/em three judges. strong/strong/p\npSome relevant details:/p\nul\nlistrongAll code emmust/em be GstrongPL/strong/strongstrong compatible/strong/li\nlistrongAll Plugins must be compatible with WordPress 2.7 and above/strong/li\nlistrongAll Plugins have to be secure and use secure coding methods. This is very important.br /\n/strong/li\nliPlugins must be made available through the a href=http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/Wordpress Extend pages/a/li\nliPlugins must be officially submitted through email and announced and discussed on the a href=http://feeds2.feedburner.com/pluginblog/Plugin Competition Blog/a. More details on submissions will be added in the last month of the competition. Release of plugin after competition start does not mean submission. You can submit your plugin way after its release to work out bugs etc./li\nliRunning time for competition = 3 months starting the 1st of May till the 31st of July/li\nliTrue Wordpress plugins only. No manual modifications can be required of users. No editing of core files allowed./li\nliYou cannot submit plugins that have been released already. Modification or re-use of existing code to achieve completely new functionality allowed./li\nliAll plugins require documentation as in the a href=http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/about/faq/Wordpress Extend pages/a./li\nliPreliminary support for the plugin has to be provided to the public./li\nliAny and all prizes/controversies/issues will be judged and decided at my sole discretion./li\nliPast winners are not eligible for this competition./li\n/ul\npPlease let us know if we can help answer any questions or if you would like to donate some money to the competition prizes. Your help will go a long way./p";}i:47;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:59:"Weblog Tools Collection: WordPress Theme Releases for 04/25";s:4: