(48, 1, '2008-03-05 22:42:36', '2008-03-06 03:42:36', '\r\n<p class="dropcap">MIT OpenCourseWare (MIT OCW) is an initiative of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) to put all of the educational materials from its undergraduate- and graduate-level courses online, free and openly available to anyone, anywhere, by the end of the year 2007. MIT OpenCourseWare can be considered as a large-scale, web-based publication of MIT course materials. The project was announced in October 2002. This project is jointly funded by the William and Flora Hewlett Foundation, the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation, and MIT. The initiative has encouraged a number of other institutions to make their course materials available as open educational resources.</p>\r\n<p class="dropcap"><a href="http://ocw.mit.edu/OcwWeb/web/courses/courses/index.htm" target="_blank"><img src="http://sealence.x10hosting.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2008/03/logo-ocw-home_new.gif" alt="MIT OpenCourseWare" /></a></p>\r\nI found many good stuff from MIT OCW, such as <u><a href="http://ocw.mit.edu/OcwWeb/Electrical-Engineering-and-Computer-Science/6-046JFall-2005/CourseHome/index.htm" target="_blank"><u>Introduction to Algorithms (SMA 5503)</u></a></u> , they also have videos for the course on the website, and you can download the videos on your computer and enjoy teching yourself.\r\n\r\nIt''s a great opportunity for anyone who want to enrich themself. It''s a fortune for us, I really appreciate their hard work. :!:', 'MIT OpenCourseWare - our open university', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'mit-opencourseware-our-open-university', '', '', '2008-03-05 23:07:28', '2008-03-06 04:07:28', '', 0, 'http://sealence.x10hosting.com/wordpress/?p=48', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(49, 1, '2008-03-05 22:45:43', '2008-03-06 03:45:43', '', 'MIT OpenCourseWare', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'mit-opencourseware', '', '', '2008-03-05 22:45:43', '2008-03-06 03:45:43', '', 48, 'http://sealence.x10hosting.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2008/03/logo-ocw-home_new.gif', 0, 'attachment', 'image/gif', 0),
(50, 1, '2008-04-16 10:27:45', '2008-04-16 15:27:45', '\r\n<p class="dropcap">Finally I arrived at Bejing at April 16th by train. It took me 24 hours, long trip. This is my first post at Beijing, and I will start my job hunting tomorrow. :)</p>\r\nI am too tired, gotta get some sleep. :(', 'April 16th,Arrived at Beijing', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'april-16tharrived-at-beijing', '', '', '2008-04-16 10:31:42', '2008-04-16 15:31:42', '', 0, 'http://sealence.x10hosting.com/wordpress/?p=50', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(51, 1, '2008-07-18 03:21:53', '2008-07-18 08:21:53', '\r\n<p class="dropcap">My dear friends, Finally I decided to work for Thomson Reuters in Beijing, and now I am busy in my boot-camp training. Many stuff need to learn, but I will try to keep this site update.</p>\r\n<a href="http://www.thomsonreuters.com" title="thomsonreuters" target="_blank">Thomson Reuters</a> is a great company, and the people here r very nice, I think I will enjoy myself here.', 'Working @ Thomson Reuters', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'working-thomson-reuters', '', '', '2008-07-18 03:25:09', '2008-07-18 08:25:09', '', 0, 'http://sealence.x10hosting.com/wordpress/?p=51', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(53, 1, '2008-09-16 22:55:37', '2008-09-17 03:55:37', '\r\n<p class="dropcap">Recently I have to work under Cygwin on windows, and use ssh to modified files on a remote solaris server. It''s necessary to keep a local copy of my files of that server, and also due to the network problem, the server is located in US, even ssh is too slow for me sometimes.</p>\r\nSo I want to work locally and synchronize my files between Cygwin and the server side. To do this, I write some bash script to download and upload files:\r\n\r\n<strong>scpdown</strong>\r\n<pre line="1" lang="bash">\r\nif [ -z "$1" ]; then\r\n    echo usage $0 : file\r\n    exit 1\r\nfi\r\n\r\nfirst=${1}\r\nsecond=${1}\r\n\r\nif [ -d "$1" ]; then\r\n    second=`dirname $first`\r\nfi\r\n\r\nif [ -f "$1" ]; then\r\n    second=$first\r\nfi\r\n\r\n#echo "$first,$second"\r\nscp -r  user@server:/homePath/$first $second</pre>\r\n<strong>scpup</strong>\r\n<pre line="1" lang="bash">\r\n#!/bin/bash\r\nif [ -z "$1" ]; then\r\n    echo usage $0 : file\r\n    exit 1\r\nfi\r\n\r\nfirst=${1}\r\nsecond=${1}\r\n\r\nif [ -d "$1" ]; then\r\n    second=`dirname $first`\r\nfi\r\n\r\nif [ -f "$1" ]; then\r\n    second=$first\r\nfi\r\n\r\n#echo "$first,$second"\r\nscp -r $first user@server:/homePath/$second</pre>\r\nusage:\r\n\r\nscpup dir/file\r\n\r\nscpdown dir/file\r\n\r\nIf you don''t wanna input your passwd when synchronize, vim ":help netrw-ssh-hack" will give what you need.\r\n\r\nSee this: <strong><a href="http://sealence.x10hosting.com/wordpress/?p=54">ssh scp no password</a></strong>', 'Use scp to synchronize local and remote files', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'use-scp-to-synchronize-local-and-remote-files', '', '\nhttp://sealence.x10hosting.com/wordpress/?p=54', '2008-09-23 20:50:34', '2008-09-24 01:50:34', '', 0, 'http://sealence.x10hosting.com/wordpress/?p=53', 0, 'post', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_category`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(54, 1, '2008-09-23 20:42:32', '2008-09-24 01:42:32', '\r\n<p class="dropcap">This hack is from vim7.2''s help doc.  “:help netrw-ssh-hack” will list it.</p>\r\n<strong>Quote here:</strong>\r\n\r\nFor Linux/Unix systems, the book “Linux Server Hacks - 100 industrial strength\r\ntips &amp; tools” by Rob Flickenger (O’Reilly, ISBN 0-596-00461-3) gives a tip\r\nfor setting up no-password ssh and scp and discusses associated security\r\nissues.  It used to be available at http://hacks.oreilly.com/pub/h/66 ,\r\nbut apparently that address is now being redirected to some “hackzine”.\r\nI’ll attempt a summary based on that article and on a communication from\r\nBen Schmidt:\r\n\r\n<strong>Method 1:</strong>\r\n\r\n1. Generate a public/private key pair on the local machine\r\n(ssh client):\r\nssh-keygen -t rsa\r\n(saving the file in ~/.ssh/id_rsa as prompted)\r\n\r\n2. Just hit the &lt;CR&gt; when asked for passphrase (twice) for no\r\npassphrase.  If you do use a passphrase, you will also need to use\r\nssh-agent so you only have to type the passphrase once per session.\r\nIf you don’t use a passphrase, simply logging onto your local\r\ncomputer or getting access to the keyfile in any way will suffice\r\nto access any ssh servers which have that key authorized for login.\r\n\r\n3. This creates two files:\r\n~/.ssh/id_rsa\r\n~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub\r\n\r\n4. On the target machine (ssh server):\r\ncd\r\nmkdir -p .ssh\r\nchmod 0700 .ssh\r\n\r\n5. On your local machine (ssh client): (one line)\r\nssh {serverhostname}\r\ncat ‘&gt;&gt;’ ‘~/.ssh/authorized_keys2′ &lt; ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub\r\n\r\nor, for OpenSSH, (one line)\r\nssh {serverhostname}\r\ncat ‘&gt;&gt;’ ‘~/.ssh/authorized_keys’ &lt; ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub\r\n\r\nYou can test it out with\r\nssh {serverhostname}\r\nand you should be log onto the server machine without further need to type\r\nanything.\r\n\r\n<strong>Method 2:</strong>\r\n\r\nIf you decided to use a passphrase, do:\r\nssh-agent $SHELL\r\nssh-add\r\nssh {serverhostname}\r\nYou will be prompted for your key passphrase when you use ssh-add, but not\r\nsubsequently when you use ssh.  For use with vim, you can use &gt;\r\nssh-agent vim\r\nand, when next within vim, use\r\n:!ssh-add\r\nAlternatively, you can apply ssh-agent to the terminal you’re planning on\r\nrunning vim in:\r\nssh-agent xterm &amp;\r\nand do ssh-add whenever you need.\r\n\r\nFor Windows, folks on the vim mailing list have mentioned that Pageant helps\r\nwith avoiding the constant need to enter the password.\r\n\r\n<strong>Method 3:</strong>\r\n\r\nKingston Fung wrote about another way to avoid constantly needing to enter\r\npasswords:\r\n\r\nIn order to avoid the need to type in the password for scp each time, you\r\nprovide a hack in the docs to set up a non password ssh account. I found a\r\nbetter way to do that: I can use a regular ssh account which uses a\r\npassword to access the material without the need to key-in the password\r\neach time. It’s good for security and convenience. I tried ssh public key\r\nauthorization + ssh-agent, implementing this, and it works! Here are two\r\nlinks with instructions:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/library/l-keyc2/" target="_blank">http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/library/l-keyc2/</a>\r\n<a href="http://sial.org/howto/openssh/publickey-auth/" target="_blank">http://sial.org/howto/openssh/publickey-auth/</a>', 'ssh scp no password', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'ssh-scp-no-password', '', '', '2008-09-24 05:16:39', '2008-09-24 10:16:39', '', 0, 'http://sealence.x10hosting.com/wordpress/?p=54', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(55, 1, '2008-12-11 00:18:17', '2008-12-11 05:18:17', '\r\n<p class="dropcap">We found a seafood wholesale market in Beijing called Jing Sheng Wholesale Food Market.</p>\r\nI brought lots of seafood there and cooked them for dinner. Check it out! :)<br/>\r\n<a href="http://picasaweb.google.com/s/c/bin/slideshow.swf" style="left: 0px ! important; top: 0px ! important" title="Click here to block this object with Adblock Plus" class="abp-objtab-00029441947450500328 visible ontop"></a><a href="http://picasaweb.google.com/s/c/bin/slideshow.swf" style="left: 0px ! important; top: 16.4px ! important" title="Click here to block this object with Adblock Plus" class="abp-objtab-00029441947450500328 visible ontop"></a><a href="http://picasaweb.google.com/s/c/bin/slideshow.swf" style="left: 0px ! important; top: 16.4px ! important" title="Click here to block this object with Adblock Plus" class="abp-objtab-00029441947450500328 visible ontop"></a><a href="http://picasaweb.google.com/s/c/bin/slideshow.swf" style="left: 0px ! important; top: 16.4px ! important" title="Click here to block this object with Adblock Plus" class="abp-objtab-00029441947450500328 visible ontop"></a><a href="http://picasaweb.google.com/s/c/bin/slideshow.swf" style="left: 0px ! important; top: 16.4px ! important" title="Click here to block this object with Adblock Plus" class="abp-objtab-00029441947450500328 visible ontop"></a><a href="http://picasaweb.google.com/s/c/bin/slideshow.swf" style="left: 0px ! important; top: 16.4px ! important" title="Click here to block this object with Adblock Plus" class="abp-objtab-00029441947450500328 visible ontop"></a><a href="http://picasaweb.google.com/s/c/bin/slideshow.swf" style="left: 0px ! important; top: 16.4px ! important" title="Click here to block this object with Adblock Plus" class="abp-objtab-00029441947450500328 visible ontop"></a><a href="http://picasaweb.google.com/s/c/bin/slideshow.swf" style="left: 0px ! important; top: 16.4px ! important" title="Click here to block this object with Adblock Plus" class="abp-objtab-00029441947450500328 visible ontop"></a><embed src="http://picasaweb.google.com/s/c/bin/slideshow.swf" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" flashvars="host=picasaweb.google.com&amp;RGB=0x000000&amp;feed=http%3A%2F%2Fpicasaweb.google.com%2Fdata%2Ffeed%2Fapi%2Fuser%2Fsealence%2Falbumid%2F5274102548459187009%3Fkind%3Dphoto%26alt%3Drss" pluginspage="http://www.macromedia.com/go/getflashplayer" height="192" width="288"></embed><br/>\r\nJing Shen wholesale seafood market is the city''s primary source of fresh fish and other aquatic delights. Nearest subway station is Songjiazhuang, line 5.\r\n\r\nAs most of Beijing''s restaurants and other markets source their produce there, prices are astonishingly cheap.\r\n\r\nEverything is sold by the jin, which equates to half a kilo.  All scallops in my picture added up to only 15 RMB. Stomatopods are around 40 RMB.\r\n\r\nAmazing, isn''t it? :P', 'Seafood in Beijing', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'seafood-in-beijing', '', '', '2008-12-11 00:43:20', '2008-12-11 05:43:20', '', 0, 'http://sealence.x10hosting.com/wordpress/?p=55', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(56, 1, '2009-01-07 22:05:50', '2009-01-08 03:05:50', '\r\n<p class="dropcap">Recently I am using a cool program to watch English TV on line. It''s called "Livestation". I use it at home in Beijing with 1Mb ADSL, the speed is really fast, more than any tools I use ever.</p>\r\n<a href="http://www.livestation.com/" title="livestation"><img src="http://assets2.livestation.com/images/livestation_logo_narrow_with_strapline.gif" alt="livestation" height="47" width="216" /></a>\r\n\r\nIt''s a good way to learn English by watching people how to say it, and now I can watch BBC, CNN, FOX, CBS in Beijing. What a wonderful world technology made it!\r\n\r\n<img src="http://sealence.x10hosting.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009/01/livestation.png" alt="livestation" />\r\n\r\nMore importantly, this tool can be use on multiple platforms: Mac, Linux, Windows.', 'Watch English TV on line', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'watch-english-tv-on-line', '', '', '2009-01-07 22:43:28', '2009-01-08 03:43:28', '', 0, 'http://sealence.x10hosting.com/wordpress/?p=56', 0, 'post', '', 0),
